## Bug

**Target**
K64F

**Toolchain:**
GCC_ARM

**Toolchain version:**
4.9.3

**meed-os sha:**
269f58d75b752a4e67a6a2d8c5c698635ffd6752

**Expected behavior**

The Hue bridge closes the connection straight after returning a request. This is causing LWIP to drop packets. This issue does not show on ESP8266.

Here's an example program:

```cpp
#include "mbed.h"
#include "easy-connect.h"
#include <string>

Serial pc(USBTX, USBRX);

int main() {
    pc.baud(115200);
    // Connect to the network (see mbed_app.json for the connectivity method used)
    NetworkInterface *network = easy_connect(true);
    if (!network) {
        printf("Cannot connect to the network, see serial output");
        return 1;
    }

    TCPSocket socket;
    socket.open(network);
    socket.connect("192.168.1.10", 80);

    const char req[] = "POST /api HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: 10.2.202.46\r\nContent-Length: 41\r\n\r\n{ \"devicetype\": \"mbed_hue#elektor_demo\" }";

    socket.send(req, sizeof(req));

    uint8_t* buffer = (uint8_t*)malloc(8 * 1024);
    uint8_t* orig_buffer = buffer;

    size_t recv_ret = 0;

    while ((recv_ret = socket.recv(buffer, 1024)) > 0) {
        buffer += recv_ret;
    }

    printf("total bytes %d\r\n", buffer - orig_buffer);

    std::string blah((const char*)orig_buffer, static_cast<size_t>(buffer - orig_buffer));

    printf("return value is:\r\n%s\r\n", blah.c_str());


    Thread::wait(osWaitForever);
}
```

If you press the 'link' button on the Hue bridge the program returns this:

```
total bytes 17
return value is:
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
```

This is not correct. The bridge actually sends two TCP packets, one 17 bytes and another one 481 bytes. The ESP8266 driver does correctly receive two TCP packets... Somehow we're losing packets. When looking at the Wireshark logs we correctly see two TCP packets go by over the network interface, so it looks like an LWIP bug.

@sg-  @matthewelse

## Bug

**Target**
EFM32 (tested on EFM32HG_STK3400 and EFM32LG_STK3600)

**Toolchain:**
GCC_ARM

**Toolchain version:**
4.9.3

**mbed-cli version:** 
1.0.0

**meed-os sha:**
f4864dc64

**Expected behavior**
When combining synchronous writes to serial (i.e `Serial.printf`, `Serial.puts` or `Serial.putc`) with asynchronous writes (i.e `Serial.write`) the asynchronous write is expected to work properly (assuming no race-conditions). This means the system is supposed to be able to go to a low power sleep mode when the data has been sent.

**Actual behavior**
When the data has been sent, the MCU does not go to a proper low-power sleep mode or something else is causing a higher-than-expected power consumption. Following scope image is taken from an EFM32HG_STK3400 dev board sending data using `Serial.printf` at boot and echoing received lines using Serial.write using the Low Energy UART:
![bug on EFM32HG_STK3400](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1408377/24610019/4eea8c48-187d-11e7-8969-3798e0e5da3a.png)

The same code on the EFM32LG_STK3600 target causes the same issue (with a slightly higher power consumption):
![bug on EFM32LG_STK3600](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1408377/24610166/d7242aec-187d-11e7-935a-69ff630fdf0b.png)

When not sending the initial data using `Serial.printf` the issue does not occur (on EFM32LG_STK3600 board):
![no printf on EFM32LG_STK3600](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1408377/24610532/36a9dd1c-187f-11e7-8687-27d990e99932.png)

And when using only synchronous writes the issue does not occur either:
![puts on EFM32LG_STK3600](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1408377/24610679/ca89ec84-187f-11e7-979b-31de0061eb8c.png)

**Steps to reproduce**
- Program following code on an EFM32 target, [make sure to compile using release target](https://github.com/ARMmbed/mbed-os/issues/4082):
``` cpp
#include "mbed.h"

#define RX_BUFFER_SIZE 10

DigitalOut led(LED0);
Serial leuart(PD4, PD5);
event_callback_t serialEventCb;
uint8_t rx_buf[RX_BUFFER_SIZE];

void serialCb(int events) {
    unsigned char i;
    if(events & SERIAL_EVENT_RX_CHARACTER_MATCH) {
        for(i = 0; i < RX_BUFFER_SIZE; i++) {
            if(rx_buf[i] == '\n') break;
        }
    } else if (events & SERIAL_EVENT_RX_COMPLETE) {
        i = RX_BUFFER_SIZE - 1;
    } else {
        led = 1;
    }
    leuart.write(rx_buf, i+1, 0, 0);
    leuart.read(rx_buf, RX_BUFFER_SIZE, serialEventCb, SERIAL_EVENT_RX_ALL, '\n');
}

int main()
{
    leuart.printf("Hello, world\r\n");

    serialEventCb.attach(serialCb);
    leuart.read(rx_buf, RX_BUFFER_SIZE, serialEventCb, SERIAL_EVENT_RX_ALL, '\n');

    while(true) {
        sleep();
    }
    return 0;
}
```
- Measure the current draw from the battery, make sure to put the current source select switch to `BAT` and to disconnect the debugger.
- In scope images, current drawn was measured using a [Current](https://www.eevblog.com/projects/ucurrent/) connected to Channel 1. Channel 2 was connected to pin `PD4`. The battery power was supplied by a 3V3 power supply.

## Notes
- 1mA in the scope images is actually 1A. This is caused by the output unit of the Current being set to 1mV/A and the Scope using a 1X probe configuration (sadly X0.001 is not available on the Rigol DS1054).
- The range of the Current is limited to 1.5mV, so the maximum current that can be measured is 1500A or 1.5mA.
- When sending a new character to the MCU the power consumption seems to go down again.

